  <p>Hi, I'm <b>Matt</b>. I've been smiling for the last {{years.experience}} years because I'm a full-stack developer. You might be wondering "what is that?" Well, it's someone that does both front-end and back-end development. Front-end being the stuff you see on the web and back-end being the stuff you don't -- generally web developers fall into either category, it's rare to pursue both to any great extent as I have.</p>
  <p>Not to get too technical, but my preferred front-end technologies are HTML5, CSS3, and JavaScript and my preferred back-end technologies are Linux (Ubuntu/CentOS), LXD/LXC, Apache2, PHP7, Python (scripts only), MySQL. That's not to say I haven't learn dozens of others, it's just the tools I keep in on my belt instead of my tool box. That being said, the designing systems is about more than learning technologies, which are just used just to express a idea -- it's about playing god and knowing how to. Full-stack developers should be able to design the rules of the micro universe while being omnipotent, omnipresent, omniscient, and omnibenevolent.</p>
  <p>Although I've spent years doing game, software, and even 7-axis robotic development, my focus for the last decade been the web, the system development life cycle, and designing web solutions. I chose to give up using fancy development platforms, for making users available to anyone from anywhere.</p>
  <p>I've heard some say full-stack web developers are modern myths, unicorns as it were. Let's find out!</p>
